Description: Founded in 2002 by Eric Olsen as a group blog publishing mostly reviews, Blogcritics soon grew into a full-fledged, professionally edited
Headquarters Regions: Greater Chicago Area, Great Lakes, Midwestern US
Full Description: Founded in 2002 by Eric Olsen as a group blog publishing mostly reviews, Blogcritics soon grew into a full-fledged, professionally edited online magazine with reviews, interviews, and news articles and commentary. Barbara Barnett and Jon Sobel became Executive Editors in 2010, and their company, Critical Lens Media, acquired the site in 2014. Blogcritics.org, one of the world's longest-running and most respected online publications, has been acquired by Critical Lens Media, Ltd. from former owner Technorati Media. Critical Lens, owned by Blogcritics' executive editors Barbara Barnett and Jon Sobel, will continue, and broaden, the site's coverage of the arts, pop culture and current events. The magazine will maintain its relationships with its editorial staff and its large cadre of contributors while also recruiting fresh talent. "We're very pleased that we're going to be able to steer Blogcritics in a more focused direction and keep it growing in the new age of mobile," Sobel says. "It's an excellent opportunity for us, now as editor-publishers, to build on Blogcritics’ 12-year foundation by marketing creatively, further integrating social media, and more, so the publication can reach its full potential." “I am looking forward to taking Blogcritics to the next level, deepening our coverage of music, television, books, movies, theater and current affairs,” says Barnett. “With a solid editorial vision that focuses on quality original content -- reviews, interviews, in-depth feature stories, and opinion pieces – Jon and I hope to build Blogcritics into the place to come for reading about and discussing all things entertainment, culture, and society.”
Industry Groups: Content and Publishing, Information Technology, Media and Entertainment

Headquarters Regions: Greater San Diego Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: Lambesis creates iconic brand ideas that are strategically grounded, culturally relevant and enduring. Lambesis is a full service brand development company that integrates the entire realm of research and communication to build brands. Lambesis’ capabilities include strategy, research, design, creative, interactive and web development.  For over 25 years, Lambesis has used a unique creative-driven process to create iconic brands that have garnered international recognition, consumer loyalty and, most importantly, client success. Through a proprietary process that allows diverse departments to work seamlessly together, Lambesis brand development is united by a single vision. The result is meticulously researched, intuitive and inspired communication platforms that raise brand awareness and resonate with consumers on a deep emotional level. By redefining the art of communication, Lambesis has mastered true branding. The holistic and integrated approach of Lambesis has allowed them to build dynamic brands such as Airwalk, SKYY Vodka, and bebe into billion-dollar businesses with a lasting cultural impact. Their iconic work for clients such as Tacori, Grand Marnier and DASANI showcase the scope and range of the work they have successfully executed over the years. Lambesis’ style-based approach to branding across prestige and mass prestige products ranging from fashion and spirits, to electronics and travel, to fitness and music, has gained them international recognition, with numerous textbook case studies and industry publications citing Lambesis’s success.  Malcom Gladwell's best selling book, The Tipping Point, has a chapter dedicated to Lambesis' work on the Airwalk Footwear campaign, and the innovative research methods and branding techniques the agency used to catapult the brand's success.  Located in La Jolla, California, Lambesis was founded by Nicholas Lambesis in 1987, and Chad Farmer is President and Executive Creative Director.

Headquarters Regions: Midwestern US
Full Description: The Incubation Factory has a nearly twenty-year history in identifying, accelerating, launching and governing early stage companies. By institutionalizing lessons learned from the Inc. 500 successes and applying those principles to the tech-transfer industry, the company properly addresses the needs and solves the inefficiencies of the current system. Using techniques prevalent amongst the fastest growing companies in the country, and then improving upon these based on real-world lessons, The Incubation Factory has successfully established two tranches of portfolio companies and is in the process of creating a third tranche. 1993 – 2003: TIF Tech Fund evolved from Anthony, Allan & Quinn, Inc. (“AAQ”) which was founded in 1993 by AAQ’s current CEO Dan Schmitt and two partners. AAQ successfully launched eight companies from 1993 to 2003, three of which grew rapidly enough to qualify for the Inc. 500 List of the Fastest Growing Private Companies in America. In 1997, recognizing a tremendous need and opportunity for streamlining back office claim processing for the healthcare industry, AAQ founded Advanced Business Fulfillment (“ABF”) to serve insurance companies, managed care organizations, HMOs and third-party administrators. By 2003, ABF ranked No. 23 nationally and No. 1 in Missouri on the Inc. 500 List. In July 2003, ABF was sold to publicly-traded WebMD for $260 million. Through this experience AAQ performed an in-depth study of their Inc. 500 peer group, analyzing what made these companies successful as well as why other companies fail. These findings created an opportunity to introduce a paradigm shift in the innovation process, as it was discovered that companies make the same mistakes and missed out on the same opportunities across industries and businesses.
